2026 Regular Session ENROLLED
SENATE RESOLUTION NO. 134
BY SENATOR HENRY
A RESOLUTION
To commend and congratulate Isaac Herzenberg of Metairie Park Country Day School upon
winning his fourth-consecutive Class 2A state track and field championship in the
javelin and to recognize his outstanding athletic achievements and dedication to
excellence.
WHEREAS, more than four years ago, Country Day's middle school track and field
coach, Jason Abate, encouraged then-eighth-grade student, Isaac Herzenberg, to try the
javelin, a moment that sparked a remarkable athletic career; and
WHEREAS, as a young student, Isaac embraced the challenge of learning the javelin
later reflecting that, "as an eighth grader, throwing a spear—who doesn't want to do that?",
demonstrating both enthusiasm and natural curiosity for the sport; and
WHEREAS, through years of disciplined training, Isaac has become one of the most
accomplished high school javelin throwers in Louisiana, earning four consecutive Class 2A
state track and field championships in the event; and
WHEREAS, at the 2026 Class 2A state track and field championship meet, held at
LSU's Bernie Moore Track Stadium in Baton Rouge, Isaac recorded a throw of 186 feet on
his second attempt, securing yet another state title; and
WHEREAS, Isaac's competitive standard is exceptionally high, as demonstrated by
his lifetime best throw of 219 feet, 2 inches, achieved in the summer of 2025, and his
impressive 205-foot, 4-inch throw at the 2026 regional championship meet; and
WHEREAS, Isaac attributes his success to his dedication to hard work and consistent
training during the spring and summer, acknowledging that his performance improves when
he trains diligently and declines when he takes his focus away from the event; and
WHEREAS, despite balancing multiple sports, including a pause in training during
the soccer season, Isaac returned to javelin training in February and continued to excel,
demonstrating resilience, focus, and athletic maturity; and
WHEREAS, Isaac has signed to compete in track and field for the University of
Nebraska, continuing his athletic and academic career at the collegiate level; and
